</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="67" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1909,1970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,1909,1934]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[358,428,1910,1934]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">China</collectingCountry>
, Sichuan Province, known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[904,952,1911,1935]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">type</typeStatus>
locality, where it lives at altitude of about 
<number box="[151,207,1946,1970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67" value="3400.0">3400</number>
meters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="68" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,292,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">Biology.</emphasis>
The specimens were collected on the wet bottom of a sandy stream which at the collecting time was without water. The depth of the stream was from about 
<number box="[800,870,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2 to 5</number>
metres and its width from about 
<number box="[1261,1344,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" value="6.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="2.0">2 to 10</number>
metres. Around this small valley, showing very steep sandy slopes, was present a relatively intact deciduous forest with natural tree species composition. All big trees were cut down, but the tree species composition was relatively rich.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,314,295,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">Affinities.</emphasis>
Sister species of 
<taxonomicName box="[514,624,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="farkaci">
<emphasis box="[514,624,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">B. farkaci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[641,719,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1310,1333]" captionTargetBox="[191,1389,233,1252]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1289]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 2. Habitus of 1) B. farkaci (paratype) and 2) B. kmecoi sp. nov. (holotype), scale = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277589/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[734,748,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 4" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1812,1835]" captionTargetBox="[232,1380,870,1747]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,805,1791]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 4. Median lobe of the aedeagus in left lateral view of: 3) B. farkaci (holotype) and 4) B. kmecoi sp. nov. (holotype), scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277590/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">3</figureCitation>
) with which it forms a group of species characterized by the extreme development of the eyes, a peculiar character shown only by these two species in the whole subgenus. In the other characters, e.g. foveate discal elytral pores, elytral striae sulcate and complete, and, of course, basal margin reaching stria 
<number box="[352,366,404,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" value="4.0">4</number>
with a straight portion, they are similar to most species of the subgenus.
</paragraph>
